metadata.name: The Storm ⛈ #102
metadata.description: Seemingly quiet amidst literary parlors and gilded seclusion, Emily Dickinson's life was likely at the mercy of a storm of emotions and feelings. In this work of generative art fully encoded in p5.js, the feelings of the people she lived with find an abstract representation, sometimes with fragments of her three her poems about storm.

metadata.name: Herbarium #142
metadata.description:
"Herbarium" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

Occasionally, I stumble upon vintage scientific illustrations on various topics, exotically looking charts and graphs, alternative layouts for the periodic tables or psychological research diagrams, elaborate illustrations of botany and zoology, minerals, and natural and sometimes unnatural phenomena. Most of those illustrations are part of the "art and science" practices from the 18th and 19th centuries. At the core of those practices were observation and interpretation, unraveling complexity through visualizing abstract ideas or finding a creative approach for understanding previously incomprehensible forms. 

I'm an admirer of two female pioneers in the field. Maria Sibylla Merian created, with immense dedication, a book with intricate illustrations of plants and insects, later praised by scientists. On the other hand, Anna Atkins published a book with beautiful botanical cyanotypes, considered the first book with photographic images. These topics are the visual inspiration for pieces presented at ArtBasel HK. 

My mathematical background makes me naturally attracted to graphs, converting numbers to curves, and everything schematically displayed. Also, combining scientific symbols and illustrations with imaginary data inspires the spectator to find meaning in unrelated or random things or provokes latent skepticism towards assumed concepts of truth, reality, and knowledge.

metadata.name: Window gratings 2 #71
metadata.description:
<Window gratings 2> combines 2 images in 1950s: The Window gratings in Taiwan and the Kowloon Walled City in Hong Kong.

Based on the previous experience of <Window gratings>, I rewrite all of the code and give it a totally different perspective.

More than 5,000 possible buildings & floors combinations
Tens of unique Window grating styles, balcony, and roof.
12 different color palette of buildings + 6 background.
3 different color mode lead to totally different images.

[keyboard] Press 's' to save PNG in original size

JT

metadata.name: GENAU / Pixel Incubator I #144
metadata.description:
With this piece, i wish to familiarise my fellow artists and collectors with a technique/aesthetic i've been working on for the last few months. This is the first time i ever develop a piece that, although animated, resulting to a static image. Right click to save the image. It was originally coded as an animated experience, producing infinite number of abstract portraits for a brief moment in time, rushing back to distraction and give birth to the next image; hence it's name. The piece was refactored to fit fxhash, as a platform and as a community of artists and collectors that appreciate the uniqueness of each of its iterations.

Inspired by the masters H.R.Giger and Z.Beksinski.

Hope you like your mints 🌃🌆🌄 and to be able to find something to look at and be proud to have it in your collection. 

Thank you for all the support 

- 100% real-time / Nothing preloaded, except the font.
- Original code
- Entirely build with P5

metadata.name: Circles In A Square World #115
metadata.description:
Circles In A Square World, is a play on the saying "being square", usually referring to someone who is more conventional and boring. In the society I grew up in, being square is what people are being pushed towards. A traditional 9 - 5 in a well paying office job the goal. But I believe that in a world where the majority is square, living the circle life is way more fulfilling.

For each square in Circles In A Square World there is a small chance a circle will be drawn instead. The series re-uses the palettes that were discovered in Ode to Color as well. 

To watch the drawing process press 'd'.

To get a higher resolution for printing add ?size=4096 at the end of the URL in the live view (you can use any size you want).

metadata.name: kondo #22
metadata.description:
because any respectable generative artist needs a box packing algorithm

developed in threejs. press [P] to toggle paper effect

WARNING:
due to precision discrepancies between mobile/integrated GPUs and desktop GPUs, the generated preview and the actual render might differ. this is due to the inconsistent implementation of certain high-precision math functions used in the shader for hashed box packing

metadata.name: [C]Range #30
metadata.description:
Collection [C]Range (Сertain Range) is a development by the artist of the idea that our reality has a starting point and evolves (generated) by coordinates with random values; but for the appearance of a particular event (person, thought, situation), a certain range is set.

Each work of the collection is 100% unique and created with no use of pre-prepared raster or vector images. Arrow as a graphic marker indicates a starting point. Only p5.js curves with random coordinate values are used when generating but in the range specified by the artist.

And who sets this range in the reality that we feel like reality?

metadata.name: Cubick (Vintage Red) #54
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender Renders.

In each output, the four "cubes" are arranged in a calming, 'zen-like' formation.

In each output, the orientation of the "cubes", and the number and positions of the colored regions varies.

All outputs in this collection will have the same color palette (called Vintage Red).

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1375x1500px PNG.

Several "Cubick" collections will be released, each with a different color palette.

metadata.name: Isomeric doppelgangers #23
metadata.description:
'Isomeric doppelgangers' 

Spatial isomerism, is a form of isomerism in which molecules have the same molecular formula and sequence of bonded atoms (constitution), but differ in the three-dimensional orientations of their atoms in space.

This artworks flips several boxes on the X or Y axis, resulting in two gemelar images, each with the same palette but a different color mix. The perception of diverse scenes is based only on these modifications.

The collection is limited to 100 works of art.

-----

Press 's' to save the current canvas view.

-----

Features:

Palette: coral, gray, retro, vrolik3, origami, sooph, jfa, bell
Zoom: low, medium, high, random
Orientation: portrait, vertical
Fill: true, false


-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr.

Made with P5js and <3.
